Text.TextId: Help_Diag: short-circuit to sensor voltage AI
Text.Value: If you enable the check box, if there is a short circuit of the sensor power supply to M (ground) and the channel is activated, diagnostics information is generated. The sensor power supply is monitored for connectors X1, X3, X5 and X7. It is not possible to identify the connector on which the sensor short occurred.

Click this box to display and select the available types and ranges of measurement. Recommendation: You should deactivate input channels that are not connected (input type: deactivated), to reduce the scan cycle time of the modules.

With this parameter, you set the integration time of the device depending on the selected interference frequency. Here, select the frequency of the line power you are using. Interference frequency suppression "Off" means 500 Hz or Fast mode.
Here, you set the unit in which you want the temperature to be measured.

The measured values can be smoothed by digital filtering. The stronger the smoothing, the greater the time constant of the digital filter. For a description of the effects of the various smoothing factors, refer to the documentation of the module.

Select this check box for the relevant channel if you want a wire break to be detected by diagnostics. With analog input channels, wire break diagnostics is not possible for all measuring ranges and types of measurement. For a detailed description, refer to the documentation of the module.

If you select the check box, information to this effect is entered in the diagnostics area of the module. For more detailed information on the values at which underflow occurs, refer to the measuring range tables in the documentation of the module. For more detailed information on the values at which overflow occurs, refer to the measuring range tables in the documentation of the module. If the measuring point is subjected to a temperature different from the free ends of the thermocouple (connection point), a voltage is produced between the free ends, the thermal e.m.f. The strength of the thermal e.m.f. depends on the difference between the temperature of the measuring point and the temperature at the free ends and the materials used to make up the thermocouple. Since a thermocouple is always used to capture a temperature difference, the free ends at the reference junction must always be kept at a known temperature to be able to measure the temperature at the measuring point. If you set Internal compensation, the temperature of the measuring point in the housing of the I/O device is measured. If you set External compensation, you can include a compensating box to achieve greater accuracy in the temperature measurement.

If the measuring point is subjected to a temperature different from the free ends of the thermocouple (connection point), a voltage is produced between the free ends, the thermal e.m.f. The strength of the thermal e.m.f. depends on the difference between the temperature of the measuring point and the temperature at the free ends and the materials used to make up the thermocouple. Since a thermocouple is always used to capture a temperature difference, the free ends at the reference junction must always be kept at a known temperature to be able to measure the temperature at the measuring point. If you set Internal, the temperature of the measuring point in the housing of the I/O device is measured. If you set None, you can include a compensating box to achieve greater accuracy in the temperature measurement.

Text.TextId: Help_Diag: short-circuit to sensor voltage AO
Text.Value: If you enable the check box, if there is a short circuit of the sensor power supply to M (ground) and the channel is activated, diagnostics information is generated. The sensor power supply is monitored for connectors X1, X2, X3 and X4. It is not possible to identify the connector on which the sensor short occurred.

Click on the box to display the available output types and to make your selection. If you do not use a channel, select the setting "Deactivated". With a deactivated channel, the conversion and integration time of the channel = 0s and the module cycle time is optimized.

Select how the outputs of the modules should react if the CPU goes into the STOP mode:
- Outputs have no current or voltage (OCV) if the module should switch off the outputs in the STOP mode (E/I = 0 V/mA).
- Keep last value (KLV) if the module should keep the last value output before STOP.
- Substitute a value (SV) The default substitute value is "0", You can set the substitute values for each individual output in the "Substitute Value" row.
Attention: Make sure that the system is always in a safe state when substitute values are output!
Here, you enter a substitute value that the module will output when the CPU is in STOP. The substitute value must be in the nominal range, overrange or underrange.

If you select this check box, the check of the output for short circuit is activated. Short circuits can only be detected for the voltage output type. In the zero range, this diagnostic information cannot be detected.

Select this check box for the corresponding output to activate wire break diagnostics.Wire break can only be detected with the current output type! In the zero range, this diagnostic information cannot be detected.
If you select the check box, this enables the check for overload. For more information on overload diagnostics, refer to the manual of the module.
The reference temperature applies to all channels for which 'reference junction' 'Fix Ref. Temp.' has been selected. The value must be multiplied by 10, regardless of the temperature unit (C, F, K).

If the measuring point is subjected to a temperature different from the free ends of the thermocouple (connection point), a voltage is produced between the free ends, the thermal e.m.f. The strength of the thermal e.m.f. depends on the difference between the temperature of the measuring point and the temperature at the free ends and the materials used to make up the thermocouple. Since a thermocouple is always used to capture a temperature difference, the free ends at the reference junction must always be kept at a known temperature to be able to measure the temperature at the measuring point. If you set Internal compensation, the temperature of the measuring point in the housing of the I/O device is measured. If you set External compensation, you can include a compensating box to achieve greater accuracy in the temperature measurement.
